<br>
People are always gonna view statements differently.  One person's compliment is another person's insult.<br>
<br>
My best advice is that if you know something is gonna offend someone, and you can make the exact same point phrasing it in a non-offensive manner, it's not a bad thing to do so.  If you think &quot;that's so gay&quot; is perfectly interchangable with &quot;that's so dumb&quot; why use the former (if there's someone around to be offended)?<br>
<br>
On the flip side, if you go through life getting offended by every little thing you're gonna have a hella sucky life.  You can consider yourself to be &quot;Political Correctness Superhero/heroine&quot; and look down on every person you feel has a flaw, and eventually you're gonna end up looking down on the entire world because no one's perfect (not even you, especially considering how many are glad to be prejudiced in the other direction).<br>
<br>
If you wanna discuss the semantics of &quot;that's so gay&quot; and how it can, or can't be read as an offensive term, feel free.  If you start wandering too far into trashing eachother over your differing views, or start lobbing accusations / insinuations at eachother, someone's prolly gonna lock this.  Consider it fair warning.<br>
